hands_on_practices.solution:
We have three identical atoms at the vertices of an equilateral triangle of side length $R$. 

1. Pairwise London dispersion energy (three pairs):  
$$U_{\rm pair} = 3\biggl(-\frac{C_6}{R^6}\biggr) = -\frac{3\,C_6}{R^6}\,. $$

2. Three-body Axilrod–Teller–Muto potential:  
$$U_{\rm ATM}
= C_9\;\frac{1+3\cos\theta_1\cos\theta_2\cos\theta_3}
{R_{12}^3R_{23}^3R_{31}^3}\,. $$  
For an equilateral triangle, $\theta_1=\theta_2=\theta_3=60^\circ$, so $\cos\theta_k=\tfrac12$ and  
$$1+3\cos\theta_1\cos\theta_2\cos\theta_3
=1+3\Bigl(\tfrac12\Bigr)^3
=1+\tfrac{3}{8}
=\tfrac{11}{8}\,. $$  
Since $R_{12}=R_{23}=R_{31}=R$,  
$$U_{\rm ATM}
= C_9\,\frac{11/8}{R^9}
=\frac{11\,C_9}{8\,R^9}\,. $$

3. Ratio of three-body to total pairwise energy:  
$$\frac{U_{\rm ATM}}{U_{\rm pair}}
=\frac{\dfrac{11\,C_9}{8\,R^9}}{-\dfrac{3\,C_6}{R^6}}
=-\frac{11\,C_9}{8\,R^9}\;\frac{R^6}{3\,C_6}
=-\frac{11\,C_9}{24\,C_6\,R^3}\,. $$

4. Substitute $C_9=\gamma\,\alpha_0\,C_6$:  
$$\frac{U_{\rm ATM}}{U_{\rm pair}}
=-\frac{11\,(\gamma\,\alpha_0\,C_6)}{24\,C_6\,R^3}
=-\frac{11\,\gamma\,\alpha_0}{24\,R^3}\,. $$
